MEDIUM|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:53|enforceConstraints has no self-defense against max_findings <= 0. The guard len(findings) > *maxFindings fires for 0, all findings are sorted, then findings[:0] discards ALL of them while stderr reports "truncated to max_findings 0" — a silent total drop disguised as a cap. It relies entirely on registry validation (config.go max_findings > 0) in a different package; any direct caller or future config path that bypasses that single guard silently destroys an agent's entire output.|In enforceConstraints, treat *maxFindings <= 0 as "no cap" (skip the truncation block) rather than truncate-to-zero, mirroring the absent-cap behavior. Add a unit test passing maxFindings=0 asserting all findings pass through with truncated==0.|error-handling|15|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:53-60|claude
MEDIUM|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:17|The severity-rank rubric {CRITICAL:4,HIGH:3,MEDIUM:2,LOW:1} is independently redefined in fanout/postprocess.go:17, reconcile/merge.go, verify, report, plus a set-form copy reviewSeverities in registry/config.go. postprocess looks up severityRank[strings.ToUpper(...)] while reconcile looks up the raw value, so a future severity change or a non-canonical casing silently desyncs fan-out truncation from reconcile merging. The postprocess copy was newly added by Epic 2.2.|Extract a single canonical severity package (or export from internal/stream) exposing the ordered rank map plus normalizeSeverity, and have registry/fanout/reconcile/verify/report consume it. Verify by deleting the local maps and confirming the suite passes with one source of truth.|maintainability|120|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:12-17|claude
MEDIUM|internal/fanout/review.go:600|buildFallbackAgent overrides the fallback's MinSeverity/MaxFindings with the primary's (review.go:603-604) and the fallback's Scope never reaches it (Prompt is copied from primary.Prompt which already baked in ScopeFocus(primary.Scope)). A user who sets scope/min_severity/max_findings on an agent that only ever runs as a fallback gets them silently ignored, with no warning. This is a deliberate "constraints follow the slot" decision but has zero test coverage in all four 2.2 test files.|Add a test that builds a slot whose fallback declares its own min_severity/max_findings/scope and asserts the primary's constraints win. Optionally emit a load-time warning when a fallback-only agent sets these fields so the silent-ignore is visible.|testing|60|internal/fanout/review.go:582-611|claude
MEDIUM|internal/fanout/postprocess_test.go:60|TestEnforceConstraints tests over-cap and under-cap but never maxFindings == len(findings) — the exact boundary where the len(findings) > *maxFindings guard flips. It also never feeds an unknown/garbage or mixed-case severity (e.g. "BLOCKER", "high") into a finding, so the severityRank[...]==0 fallback and the finding-side strings.ToUpper at postprocess.go:39 are unexercised; a regression changing > to >= or deleting the ToUpper would not be caught.|Add a case with maxFindings=len(in) asserting no truncation and order preserved; add a case with a "BLOCKER"/"" finding under a LOW floor asserting it is dropped; add a case with a lower-case finding severity exercising the finding-side normalization.|testing|30|internal/fanout/postprocess_test.go:60-71|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:35|When min_severity is a non-empty but unknown value, severityRank[floor] returns 0; every real severity ranks >= 1, so >= 0 keeps everything — the floor silently becomes a no-op and emits no warning, contradicting the doc claim that it "drops every finding below the floor." Safe today only because registry load canonicalizes and validates min_severity; the function itself fails open.|Look up floorRank, ok := severityRank[floor] and if !ok either skip enforcement with a loud stderr warning or treat as a programming error. Add a test passing minSeverity="bogus" asserting the chosen contract.|error-handling|15|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:35-49|claude
LOW|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:37|enforceConstraints filters in place via kept := findings[:0], overwriting the caller's backing array, and the later sort.SliceStable reorders that same array. Safe today because the only caller (findingsFor) passes a freshly-parsed slice it never reuses, but it is a latent aliasing trap: any future caller holding the pre-enforcement slice (e.g. a before/after diagnostic) would see its data silently clobbered and reordered.|Allocate kept := make([]stream.Finding, 0, len(findings)) to keep the input immutable, or assert the precondition at the call site. Add a test asserting the original slice is unchanged after enforceConstraints.|correctness|15|internal/fanout/postprocess.go:37-58|claude
